  "prompt": "Why Microsoft Onedrive cannot handle long file paths?",
  "response": "Microsoft OneDrive has historically struggled with long file paths due to limitations in the Windows operating system. Here are the key reasons:\n\n1. Windows Path Length Limitation\n- Traditionally, Windows had a 260-character path length limit (MAX_PATH)\n- This limitation is deeply rooted in the Windows API and file system design\n\n2. Historical Design Constraints\n- Early Windows versions used 8.3 file naming conventions\n- PATH_MAX was set to 260 characters, including drive letter, folders, and filename\n\n3. Technical Details\n- File paths include full directory structure and filename\n- Each character and directory separator counts towards the total length\n- Exceeding 260 characters causes file operations to fail\n\n4. Legacy System Compatibility\n- Many Windows APIs still maintain this legacy limitation\n- Some Windows applications and libraries haven't been updated to handle longer paths\n\n5. Partial Mitigation\n- Windows 10 version 1607 and later support longer paths with group policy or manifest changes\n- Windows can enable \"Long Path\" support, but it's not default\n\n6. OneDrive Specific Challenges\n- Syncing complex directory structures\n- Handling files from different systems with longer path requirements\n- Maintaining compatibility across Windows versions\n\n7. Workarounds\n- Use shorter file/folder names\n- Reorganize directory structure\n- Enable long path support in Windows settings\n\nModern Windows versions are improving path length handling, but legacy constraints still impact some file operations.",
